    <node id="Peter has been out of school for only two years. After getting his degree, he joined an electrical manufacturing company for a post-graduate training program. However, Lexington refers to this experience as being &quot;stockpiled&quot; by the company, meaning that Peter was trained in specific skills and knowledge that would be useful only within that company, while his broader engineering skills were allowed to become weaker. Peter admits that he could use a refresher course in calculus and other subjects that were not covered during his training program. He also mentions that the training involved using outdated equipment and methods from the 1950s. Overall, while Peter gained some practical experience during his post-graduate training program, it did not contribute significantly to his engineering skills or knowledge." />
