    <node id="The central control mechanism of the business machines in Lexington's office performs various tasks such as sorting incoming mail, replying to inquiries, preparing purchase orders, keeping track of pennies, billing customers, and collecting money. However, most of these tasks are not performed by humans but by the automated machinery controlled by the central system.&#10;&#10;Incoming mail is sorted and replied to in a small room where a teletype machine can be heard clattering away without any human operator. The incoming mail is sorted based on pre-programmed instructions and responses, and if there are any letters that the system cannot deal with, they are handled by Lexington himself.&#10;&#10;Purchase orders are prepared in another room, where an automatic bookkeeper keeps track of pennies and bills customers. When an order is received, it is translated into internal catalogue numbers used within the plant, and machines withdraw the necessary materials from stock, make component parts, assemble them, and package the finished goods for shipment. Simultaneously, an order is sent to the billing section to bill the customer, and an order is sent to the trucking company to come and pick up the shipment. If the withdrawal of materials required depletes the stock, the purchasing section is instructed to order more raw materials.&#10;&#10;The central control mechanism also handles various patterns of activity established by Lexington, although he had to add a &quot;kicker circuit&quot; to motivate the machine to activate certain functions manually. This was done to ensure that the machine's prime purpose was to activate the kicker, which could only be done manually by Lexington. The machine would then learn from Lexington's behavior and adjust its operations accordingly, allowing for more efficient and profitable business operations." />
    <node id=" for an exit, but his apprehension was unnecessary. The machines seemed to know where they were and avoided the two men, or stopped to wait for them to go by.&#10; &#10; Back in the office section of the building, Lexington indicated a small room where a typewriter could be heard clattering away. &quot;Standard business machines, operated by the central control mechanism. In that room,&quot; he said, as the door swung open and Peter saw that the typewriter was actually a sort of teletype, with no one before the keyboard, &quot;incoming mail is sorted and inquiries are replied to. In this one over here, purchase orders are prepared, and across the hall there's a very similar rig set up in conjunction with an automatic bookkeeper to keep track of the pennies and to bill the customers.&quot;&#10; &#10; &quot;Then all you do is read the incoming mail and maintain the machinery?&quot; asked Peter, trying to shake off the feeling of open amazement that had engulfed him.&#10; &#10; &quot;I don't even do those things, except for a few letters that come in every week that—it doesn't want to deal with by itself.&quot;&#10; &#10; The shock of what he had just seen was showing plainly on Peter's face when they walked back into" />
