    <node id="Based on the story, Peter Manners' impression of his job interview with Mr. Lexington is one of surprise and confusion. The office itself is much more luxurious than he expected, giving him the feeling of being in Hollywood rather than a factory. Mr. Lexington, described as a &quot;citadel of a man,&quot; interviews him in an overbearing manner, asking pointed questions about his qualifications and experience. During the interview, Mr. Lexington reveals that the factory produces medical equipment and supplies, and expresses frustration with the industry's outdated notions of specialization.&#10;&#10;Peter is left reeling after witnessing a highly automated production process that includes robotic arms and machines performing tasks that would typically require human labor. The shock of this experience is evident on his face when he returns to Mr. Lexington's office. Throughout the interview, Mr. Lexington challenges Peter's qualifications for the job, leading him to question why the company would consider hiring someone with limited practical experience. Despite these concerns, Mr. Lexington offers Peter a job, citing a shortage of skilled workers and the importance of the company's stockpiles in maintaining market competitiveness.&#10;&#10;In summary, Peter Manners is impressed by the lavishness of the office and the advanced technology he witnesses during his interview with Mr. Lexington. However, he is also confused by Mr. Lexington's challenging demeanor and apparent lack of confidence in his abilities. Despite these concerns, Peter remains interested in the job opportunity, which could provide him with valuable experience and a chance to make a difference in the medical field." />
