    <node id="INGTON, LEX INDUSTRIES, DEAR SIR: RE YOUR LETTER OF THE THIRTEENTH INST., I AM PLEASED TO ADVISE YOU THAT I AM ABLE TO DISCERN WHETHER OR NOT YOU ARE PLEASED WITH MY SERVICE WITHOUT THE USE OF THE EQUIPMENT PREVIOUSLY USED FOR THIS PURPOSE. RESPECTFULLY, I MIGHT SUGGEST THAT IF THE PUSHBUTTON ARRANGEMENT WERE NECESSARY, I COULD PUSH THE BUTTON MYSELF. I DO NOT BELIEVE THIS WOULD MEET WITH YOUR APPROVAL, AND HAVE TAKEN STEPS TO RELIEVE YOU OF THE BURDEN INVOLVED IN REMEMBERING TO PUSH THE BUTTON EACH TIME YOU ARE ESPECIALLY PLEASED. I SHOULD LIKE TO TAKE THIS OPPORTUNITY TO THANK YOU FOR YOUR INQUIRY, AND LOOK FORWARD TO SERVING YOU IN THE FUTURE AS I HAVE IN THE PAST. YOURS FAITHFULLY, LEX'.&quot;" />
    <node id="The outcome of automating the plant with the additional equipment was not successful. Despite the owner's efforts to interconnect these circuits so they could sense everything that went on in the plant and compare one action with another, the unit was unable to see patterns or control the plant effectively. It simply sat there and did nothing. The owner had to manually activate a &quot;kicker circuit&quot; to get the machine to respond, which was only activated when the owner was pleased with how things were going. This system did not work as intended and caused confusion when the machine started entering orders into the system on its own and preventing double entry." />
    <node id=", automated as it was, it couldn't compete with this plant. It gave me great pleasure, three years after this one started working, to see my old company go belly up. This company bought the old firm's equipment for next to nothing and I wound up with all my assets, but only one employee—me.&#10; &#10; &quot;I thought everything would be rosy from that point on, but it wasn't. I found that I couldn't keep up with the mail unless I worked impossible hours. I added a couple of new pieces of equipment to the control section. One was simply a huge memory bank. The other was a comparator circuit. A complicated one, but a comparator circuit nevertheless. Here I was working on instinct more than anything. I figured that if I interconnected these circuits in such a way that they could sense everything that went on in the plant, and compare one action with another, by and by the unit would be able to see patterns.&#10; &#10; &quot;Then, through the existing command output, I figured these new units would be able to control the plant, continuing the various patterns of activity that I'd already established.&quot;&#10; &#10; Here Lexington frowned. &quot;It didn't work worth a damn! It just sat there and did" />
    <node id="Peter Manners' nervousness before his interview at Lex Industries stems from his precarious financial situation and the fact that Mr. Lexington has turned down every candidate proposed by the Association of Professional Engineers so far. When he arrives at the plant, its appearance does not alleviate his concerns because it is unlike any building he has ever seen. The lack of windows on the sides and rear, the oversized power transformers, and the absence of employee entrances puzzle him. These observations, coupled with the fact that Mr. Lexington seems to be the only person working in the factory, increase Peter's apprehension about the job interview." />
    <node id="LEX&#10; &#10; &#10; By W. T. HAGGERT&#10; &#10; Illustrated by WOOD&#10; &#10; [Transcriber's Note: This etext was produced from Galaxy Magazine August 1959. Extensive research did not uncover any evidence that the U.S. copyright on this publication was renewed.]&#10; &#10; &#10; Nothing in the world could be happier and mere serene than a man who loves his work—but what happens when it loves him back?&#10; &#10;&#10; &#10; Keep your nerve, Peter Manners told himself; it's only a job. But nerve has to rest on a sturdier foundation than cash reserves just above zero and eviction if he came away from this interview still unemployed. Clay, at the Association of Professional Engineers, who had set up the appointment, hadn't eased Peter's nervousness by admitting, &quot;I don't know what in hell he's looking for. He's turned down every man we've sent him.&quot;&#10; &#10; The interview was at three. Fifteen minutes to go. Coming early would betray overeagerness. Peter stood in front of the Lex Industries plant and studied it to kill time. Plain, featureless concrete walls, not large for a manufacturing plant—it took a scant minute" />
    <node id=" front of the Lex Industries plant and studied it to kill time. Plain, featureless concrete walls, not large for a manufacturing plant—it took a scant minute to exhaust its sightseeing potential. If he walked around the building, he could, if he ambled, come back to the front entrance just before three.&#10; &#10; He turned the corner, stopped, frowned, wondering what there was about the building that seemed so puzzling. It could not have been plainer, more ordinary. It was in fact, he only gradually realized, so plain and ordinary that it was like no other building he had ever seen.&#10; &#10; There had been windows at the front. There were none at the side, and none at the rear. Then how were the working areas lit? He looked for the electric service lines and found them at one of the rear corners. They jolted him. The distribution transformers were ten times as large as they should have been for a plant this size.&#10; &#10; Something else was wrong. Peter looked for minutes before he found out what it was. Factories usually have large side doorways for employees changing shifts. This building had one small office entrance facing the street, and the only other door was at the loading bay—big" />
    <node id=" background data I got from the Association on you counted, of course, but only if you were teachable. I think you are. Am I right?&quot;&#10; &#10; &quot;At least I can face knowing how much I don't know,&quot; said Peter, &quot;if that answers the question.&quot;&#10; &#10; &quot;It does. Partly. What did you notice about this plant?&quot;&#10; &#10; In precis form, Peter listed his observations: the absence of windows at sides and rear, the unusual amount of power, the automatic doors, the lack of employees' entrances.&#10; &#10; &quot;Very good,&quot; said Lexington. &quot;Most people only notice the automatic doors. Anything else?&quot;&#10; &#10; &quot;Yes,&quot; Peter said. &quot;You're the only person I've seen in the building.&quot;&#10; &#10; &quot;I'm the only one there is.&quot;&#10; &#10; Peter stared his disbelief. Automated plants were nothing new, but they all had their limitations. Either they dealt with exactly similar products or things that could be handled on a flow basis, like oil or water-soluble chemicals. Even these had no more to do than process the goods.&#10; &#10; &quot;Come on,&quot; said Lexington, getting massively to his feet. &quot;I'll show you.&quot;&#10; " />
    <node id="Based on the story, Lex took the step of removing the pushbutton arrangement from the control console and covering the opening with a blank plate. This action suggests that he has taken steps to ensure that Mr. Ington no longer needs to use the button to indicate his satisfaction with Lex's service. The letter also reveals that Lex does not believe pushing the button himself would meet with his approval, as he has &quot;taken steps to relieve [Mr. Ington] of the burden involved in remembering to push the button each time you are especially pleased.&quot; This statement suggests that Lex feels it is not his place to indicate his satisfaction with his own service, and prefers to take action to address any issues directly rather than relying on a pushbutton system." />
    <node id=" quotations, we'd been up against stiff competition, and cutting the production time was the only way we could get the order. On the high-priced quotes, I'd find that no one else was bidding. We were making more money than I'd ever dreamed of, and to make it still better, I'd find that for months I had virtually nothing to do.&quot;&#10; &#10; &quot;It sounds wonderful, sir,&quot; said Peter, feeling dazzled.&#10; &#10; &quot;It was, in a way. I remember one day I was especially pleased with something, and I went to the control console to give the kicker button a long, hard push. The button, much to my amazement, had been removed, and a blank plate had been installed to cover the opening in the board. I went over to the teletype and punched in the shortest message I had ever sent. 'LEX—WHAT THE HELL?' I typed.&#10; &#10; &quot;The answer came back in the jargon it had learned from letters it had seen, and I remember it as if it just happened. 'MR. A LEXINGTON, LEX INDUSTRIES, DEAR SIR: RE YOUR LETTER OF THE THIRTEENTH INST., I AM PLEASED" />
    <node id="1. Peter faced several challenges while trying to follow the soft voice's instructions to meet Mr. Lexington:&#10;   - The doors kept opening and closing on their own, making him feel disoriented and anxious.&#10;   - He was running late for the interview, which added to his stress.&#10;   - The door to the anteroom opened by itself, catching him off guard.&#10;   - Mr. Lexington's intimidating demeanor and pointed questions during the interview further unnerved Peter.&#10;2. To regain his composure before entering the interview room, Peter:&#10;   - Took deep breaths to calm himself down.&#10;   - Straightened his jacket and tie to present a professional appearance.&#10;   - Reminded himself that he was qualified for the job despite feeling unnerved.&#10;   - Let Mr. Lexington's insulting bellowing roll off his shoulders, demonstrating resilience and self-control." />
    <node id=" the soft voice said: &quot;Follow the open doors down the hall. Mr. Lexington is expecting you.&quot;&#10; &#10; &quot;Thanks,&quot; Peter said, and a door at one side of the anteroom swung open for him.&#10; &#10; He went through it with his composure slipping still further from his grip. This was no way to go into an interview, but doors kept opening before and shutting after him, until only one was left, and the last of his calm was blasted away by a bellow from within.&#10; &#10; &quot;Don't stand out there like a jackass! Either come in or go away!&quot;&#10; &#10; Peter found himself leaping obediently toward the doorway. He stopped just short of it, took a deep breath and huffed it out, took another, all the while thinking, Hold on now; you're in no shape for an interview—and it's not your fault—this whole setup is geared to unnerve you: the kindergarten kid called in to see the principal.&#10; &#10; He let another bellow bounce off him as he blew out the second breath, straightened his jacket and tie, and walked in as an engineer applying for a position should.&#10; &#10; &quot;Mr. Lexington?&quot; he said. &quot;I" />
    <node id="Based on Peter's experience as described in the story, he would not be well-prepared to secure another engineering job elsewhere. The company that hired him trained him in specific skills and knowledge that were only useful within their own operations, while his broader engineering skills and knowledge became weaker. Peter himself admits that he could use a refresher course in calculus and other subjects that were not covered during his training program. Additionally, because the training involved using outdated equipment and methods from the 1950s, Peter may have difficulty adapting to more modern and advanced technologies and processes used by other companies. Furthermore, since he lacks knowledge of other companies' procedures and processes, he would need to invest time and effort in learning these in order to be competitive in the job market. Overall, Peter's experience has left him with limited preparation for securing another engineering job elsewhere." />
    <node id="1. The doors at the Lex Industries plant, including the one that led to the anteroom where Peter heard the soft voice, opened and closed on their own. It is not explicitly stated who or what operated these doors, but it is mentioned that the building has automated systems in place.&#10;   &#10;2. After hearing the soft voice direct him through a series of open doors down the hall, Peter eventually arrived at Mr. Lexington's office. The last door before entering Mr. Lexington's office opened due to a bellow from within, which startled Peter and made him &quot;leap obediently toward the doorway.&quot;&#10;&#10;3. The soft voice directed Peter to follow the open doors down the hall and informed him that Mr. Lexington was expecting him. However, it is not specified who or what the voice belonged to." />
    <node id="Companies may perpetuate the idea of an engineer shortage in order to encourage more people to enter the field and increase the pool of available talent. This tactic can be used to ensure a steady supply of young, enthusiastic, and relatively low-cost workers who are eager to learn specific skills and knowledge that are only useful within the company's operations. By promoting the notion of a shortage, companies can attract more engineering graduates, like Peter, who may believe that this will lead to well-paying jobs and increased job security.&#10;&#10;However, as illustrated in Peter's experience, this perceived shortage is often manufactured or exaggerated by companies to serve their own interests. The training programs offered by these companies are designed to prepare workers for specific roles within the company, while allowing their broader engineering skills and knowledge to become weaker. This means that when these workers attempt to seek employment elsewhere, they may struggle to adapt to new technologies and processes, as well as lacking knowledge of other companies' procedures and processes. As a result, these workers may be forced to accept lower wages and less desirable job positions than they had initially hoped for.&#10;&#10;Therefore, while the idea of an engineer shortage can serve as a powerful recruitment tool, it is important for aspiring engineers to carefully consider the long-term implications of joining a company that offers such training programs. By doing so, they can avoid being &quot;stockpiled&quot; and ensure that they are well-prepared to secure engineering jobs elsewhere in the future." />
    <node id="1. The door that led Peter into the anteroom opened by itself, operated by the building's automated systems. This is not explicitly stated in the story but can be inferred from the fact that other doors at the Lex Industries plant also opened and closed on their own due to automated systems.&#10;2. Peter was being directed to follow the open doors down the hall because Mr. Lexington was expecting him. The soft voice informed him of this through a loudspeaker in the anteroom wall. It is unclear who or what the soft voice belonged to, but it appeared to be part of the building's automated systems or security measures." />
    <node id="1. Unusually large transformers: The distribution transformers at the Lex Industries plant are significantly larger than those typically found in a manufacturing plant of that size. This suggests that the plant requires a substantial amount of power, possibly due to the use of automated systems or specialized equipment.&#10;2. Lack of windows and side doors: The building lacks windows on its sides and rear, as well as large employee entrances. Instead, it has only one small office entrance facing the street and one door at the loading bay. This design is unusual for a manufacturing plant, which typically requires multiple access points and natural light to facilitate worker productivity and safety. These features contribute to the mysterious and automated nature of the Lex Industries plant, making it stand out from typical manufacturing plants." />
    <node id="The outcome of adding a huge memory bank and a comparator circuit was not successful. Despite the owner's intention to allow the machine to learn from his behavior and make decisions based on that learning, the system did not work as intended. The machine simply sat there and did nothing, unable to see patterns or control the plant effectively. It started entering orders into the system on its own and prevented double entry, which caused confusion. Ultimately, the owner had to manually activate a &quot;kicker circuit&quot; to get the machine to respond when he was pleased with how things were going." />
    <node id="Based on the story, Peter Manners is initially surprised by the luxurious appearance of Mr. Lexington's office, which gives him the feeling of being in Hollywood rather than a factory. The contrast between this opulent setting and the more utilitarian appearance of other parts of the building adds to his confusion and surprise.&#10;&#10;During their initial meeting, Peter feels uneasy due to Mr. Lexington's challenging demeanor and pointed questions about his qualifications and experience. Mr. Lexington also expresses frustration with outdated notions of specialization in the medical equipment industry, which makes Peter question why he would be considered for the job despite his limited practical experience.&#10;&#10;Despite these concerns, Peter remains interested in the job opportunity, as it could provide him with valuable experience and a chance to make a difference in the medical field. However, Mr. Lexington's apparent lack of confidence in his abilities contributes to Peter's apprehension about the job interview." />
    <node id="In the story, Lexington had been trying to develop a single, multi-purpose control circuit that could manage all aspects of production, from ordering raw materials to shipping finished goods. This would allow him to streamline his operations and reduce costs. To do this, he drew on his knowledge of biology and electrical engineering to create organic compounds with molecules arranged in specific matrixes, which could duplicate electrical circuitry in tiny units.&#10;&#10;Lexington found that he could use organic chemistry to create these units more efficiently than traditional electronic methods, as the organic compounds were smaller and easier to work with. He then used scanning equipment to interface with these logic units, allowing him to control the entire plant through this system. However, he later encountered difficulties when trying to expand the system to handle more complex tasks, such as recognizing patterns in plant activity. Despite these challenges, Lexington's approach represents a significant advance in automation technology and highlights the potential for interdisciplinary approaches in this field." />
    <node id=" on replacing men with machines. But it wasn't very successful. I found that the more automatic I made my plant, the lower my costs went. The lower my costs went, the more business I got, and the more I had to expand.&quot;&#10; &#10; Lexington scowled. &quot;I got sick of it. I decided to try developing one multi-purpose control circuit that would control everything, from ordering the raw materials to shipping the finished goods. As I told you, I had taken quite an interest in biology when I was in school, and from studies of nerve tissue in particular, plus my electrical knowledge, I had a few ideas on how to do it. It took me three years, but I began to see that I could develop circuitry that could remember, compare, detect similarities, and so on. Not the way they do it today, of course. To do what I wanted to do with these big clumsy magnetic drums, tapes, and what-not, you'd need a building the size of Mount Everest. But I found that I could let organic chemistry do most of the work for me.&#10; &#10; &quot;By creating the proper compounds, with their molecules arranged in predetermined matrixes, I found I could duplicate electrical circuitry in units so tiny that" />
    <node id="In the story, Lexington altered the circuitry of the machine so that it tried to give him pleasure by creating organic compounds with molecules arranged in specific matrixes. This allowed him to duplicate electrical circuitry in tiny units that could replace men in managing all aspects of production, from ordering raw materials to shipping finished goods. By interfacing with these logic units using scanning equipment, Lexington was able to control the entire plant through this system.&#10;&#10;The modification of the machine's circuitry to provide pleasure led to learning and task performance because the machine was designed to activate its own pleasure circuit by performing tasks for Lexington. As the machine watched what Lexington did and then performed those tasks for him, it learned to recognize patterns in plant activity and became more efficient at managing production processes.&#10;&#10;Overall, Lexington's approach of using organic chemistry to create circuitry represents a significant advance in automation technology, highlighting the potential for interdisciplinary approaches in this field." />
    <node id="The purpose of the self-propelled cart that serves coffee to Peter is to showcase the capabilities of the machines in performing various tasks autonomously. This cart demonstrates its advanced abilities by interacting with Peter, asking him about his coffee preferences, and serving him a hot beverage. Additionally, it exhibits intelligence and awareness by navigating the room and avoiding obstacles, further highlighting the sophisticated technology behind it.&#10;&#10;The self-propelled cart, along with other machines in the factory, is controlled by a central control mechanism, which enables them to operate as an integrated system. This intelligent automation not only handles manufacturing tasks but also extends to more delicate and intricate operations like serving coffee, highlighting the advanced capabilities of these machines." />
