    <node id="Summary:&#10;In the story, Lexington becomes frustrated and critical when he sees the expensive, impractical coffee cups. The reason for his frustration is that these cups symbolize a larger issue he has with specialization in the factory's operations. He believes that focusing too much on specialization can lead to inefficiencies and unpractical solutions, which is exemplified by the impractical coffee cups.&#10;&#10;Answer:&#10;Lexington's frustration towards the expensive, impractical coffee cups arises from his larger issue with specialization at the factory. The cups are fragile, only hold half a cup, require matching saucers, and lose their gold leaf over time, rendering them unfit for purpose. Lexington sees these cups as an example of how excessive specialization can create inefficiencies and impractical solutions, which is why he is angry and critical about the cups, viewing them as representatives of a larger problem holding back progress in the factory." />
