ompany, while allowing their broader engineering skills and knowledge to become weaker. This means that when these workers attempt to seek employment elsewhere, they may struggle to adapt to new technologies and processes, as well as lacking knowledge of other companies' procedures and processes. As a result, these workers may be forced to accept lower wages and less desirable job positions than they had initially hoped for.&#10;&#10;Therefore, while the idea of an engineer shortage can serve as a powerful recruitment tool, it is important for aspiring engineers to carefully consider the long-term implications of joining a company that offers such training programs. By doing so, they can avoid being &quot;stockpiled&quot; and ensure that they are well-prepared to secure engineering jobs elsewhere in the future.">
