    <edge source="Peter Manners' nervousness before his interview at Lex Industries stems from his precarious financial situation and the fact that Mr. Lexington has turned down every candidate proposed by the Association of Professional Engineers so far. When he arrives at the plant, its appearance does not alleviate his concerns because it is unlike any building he has ever seen. The lack of windows on the sides and rear, the oversized power transformers, and the absence of employee entrances puzzle him. These observations, coupled with the fact that Mr. Lexington seems to be the only person working in the factory, increase Peter's apprehension about the job interview." target="Companies may perpetuate the idea of an engineer shortage in order to encourage more people to enter the field and increase the pool of available talent. This tactic can be used to ensure a steady supply of young, enthusiastic, and relatively low-cost workers who are eager to learn specific skills and knowledge that are only useful within the company's operations. By promoting the notion of a shortage, companies can attract more engineering graduates, like Peter, who may believe that this will lead to well-paying jobs and increased job security.&#10;&#10;However, as illustrated in Peter's experience, this perceived shortage is often manufactured or exaggerated by companies to serve their own interests. The training programs offered by these companies are designed to prepare workers for specific roles within the company, while allowing their broader engineering skills and knowledge to become weaker. This means that when these workers attempt to seek employment elsewhere, they may struggle to adapt to new technologies and processes, as well as lacking knowledge of other companies' procedures and processes. As a result, these workers may be forced to accept lower wages and less desirable job positions than they had initially hoped for.&#10;&#10;Therefore, while the idea of an engineer shortage can serve as a powerful recruitment tool, it is important for aspiring engineers to carefully consider the long-term implications of joining a company that offers such training programs. By doing so, they can avoid being &quot;stockpiled&quot; and ensure that they are well-prepared to secure engineering jobs elsewhere in the future.">
